{
  "doc_id": "46265",
  "text": "To get a sense of the growth penalty in question, we can resort to the estimates I reported earlier, from [CITATION_1] . The partial correlation between my index of (log) undervaluation and annual growth is 0.026 for developing countries as a whole, and 0.086 for China. The higher estimate we get for China may be due to the country's large reservoir of surplus labor and the huge gap in the productivity levels of modern and traditional parts of the economy. This estimate implies that a 20 percent appreciation would reduce China's growth rate by nearly two percentage points (0.20x0.086 = 1.72). This is a sizable effect, and a slowdown of this magnitude would push China dangerously close to the minimum threshold its leadership apparently believes is necessary to maintain social peace and avert social strife.",
